yet another slide description language & system

No more babysitting slides because of component dependencies.
The language is stupidly extensible, so you can finally stop living in cmd + c / cmd + v.
And with enough static checks, it catches stuff you missed in your slides before it gets a chance to embarrass you during the talk.

PDF rendering is native Zig plus a small Cairo/Pango C shim. Text shaping and
font fallback are handled by Pango/fontconfig, PDF pages are emitted by Cairo,
and generated PDFs are normalized with `qpdf`.

Setup:

  scripts/setup-md4c.sh
  zig build

This fetches the pinned MD4C revision into ignored `third_party/md4c/` sources
used by the Zig build.

Native PDF system dependencies:

  pkg-config cairo pango pangocairo librsvg-2.0 qpdf

Rendering SVG/PDF/raster assets and LaTeX math additionally uses:

  rsvg-convert pdftocairo pdftoppm magick pdflatex

Text fonts are resolved by Pango/fontconfig. Existing theme helpers can pass
real family names or comma-separated stacks, for example:

  font_family(body, "Hiragino Sans")
  font_stack(body, "Inter, Noto Sans CJK JP, Apple Color Emoji, Noto Color Emoji, sans-serif")
  code_font_family(sample, "JetBrains Mono, Noto Sans Mono CJK JP, monospace")

System install

  # Build a release binary
  zig build -Doptimize=ReleaseSafe

  # Install to system/user path (example)
  zig build -Doptimize=ReleaseSafe install --prefix ~/.local
  # or: sudo zig build -Doptimize=ReleaseSafe install --prefix /usr/local

You can verify:

  ss --help

